The paper presents a tool for gathering content to populate an ontology, which involves knowledge representation and management. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-categories. Additionally, the tool involves mapping tables to patterns, which suggests a database (cs.DB) component. The paper also mentions separating the user from standard ontology authoring environments, which could be related to software engineering (cs.SE) and natural language processing (cs.CL).
